How are these computations related to projections?  When we focus on a single dimension at a time, that is a sort of projection.  We are projectiong the data onto a lower dimensional space and then computing summary statistics.  But that is a projection of the _data_ and it seems like covariance requires taking the average of projections _onto the data_ as opposed to projecting the data itself.  Let's try projecting a very simple vector, $\mathbf{e}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1, 0 \end{bmatrix}^\top$ onto these data and let's see what happens in the algebra.


First, note $\mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}_i^\top \mathbf{e}_1 = \lVert \mathbf{x}_i \rVert^2 \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{x}_i}(\mathbf{e}_1)$, so for the sake of correctness we are working with a sort of scaled projection.  Second, the components of $\mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}_i^\top \mathbf{e}_1$ would be

$$ \mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}_i^\top \mathbf{e}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} x_{i,1}^2 & x_{i,1} x_{i,2} \\ x_{i,1} x_{i,2} & x_{i,2}^2  \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1\\0  \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x_{i,1}^2 \\ x_{i,1} x_{i,2}  \end{bmatrix}  \>. $$

Nothing interesting so far, but when we average these vectors over the $\mathbf{x}_i$ then we find

$$ \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_i \mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}_i^\top \mathbf{e}_1 = \dfrac{1}{n}  \begin{bmatrix} \sum_i x_{i,1}^2 \\ \sum_i x_{i,1} x_{i,2}  \end{bmatrix} \approx \begin{bmatrix} \operatorname{Var}(x_1) \\ \operatorname{Cov}(x_1, x_2)  \end{bmatrix}  \>. $$

The (scaled) projection of $\mathbf{e}_1$ onto the data provides us with the components we need to calculate the variance and the covariance. We can therefore obtain the variance of $x_1$ as 

$$ \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_i \mathbf{e}_1^\top \mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}_i^\top \mathbf{e}_1 \approx  \mathbf{e}_1^\top \mathbb{E}\left(\mathbf{x}_i \mathbf{x}_i^\top\right) \mathbf{e}_1 = \mathbf{e}_1^\top \Sigma  \mathbf{e}_1  $$

which should be unspurprising to no one. 

What has happened here?  We somehow went from a projection onto $\mathbf{e}_1$ to the variance of $x_1$.  Let's break it down:

* First, we projected each $\mathbf{e}_1$ onto each datapoint.  This produces a (scaled) projection vector which point in the directions of each datapoint.

* Then, we performed another inner product with $\mathbf{e}_1$. What exactly this the result of this? Recall that the inner rpoduct is, roughly, a measure of how collinear two vectors are (i.e. $ \mathbf{a}^\top \mathbf{b} = \lvert \mathbf{a} \rvert \lvert \mathbf{b} \rvert \cos(\theta)$) so we have average some measure of collinearity to $\mathbf{e}_1$ for each projected vector.

* Finally, we averaged the measures of collinearity.



::: {.column-page style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center;"}

